  "prompt": "How is the square root of 50 simplified?",
  "response": "To simplify the square root of 50, you can factor it into its prime components. The number 50 can be expressed as:\n\n\\[\n50 = 25 \\times 2\n\\]\n\nNow, we can take the square root:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{50} = \\sqrt{25 \\times 2}\n\\]\n\nUsing the property of square roots that states \\(\\sqrt{a \\times b} = \\sqrt{a} \\times \\sqrt{b}\\), we can rewrite it as:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{50} = \\sqrt{25} \\times \\sqrt{2}\n\\]\n\nSince \\( \\sqrt{25} = 5\\), we have:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{50} = 5 \\times \\sqrt{2}\n\\]\n\nThus, the simplified form of \\(\\sqrt{50}\\) is:\n\n\\[\n5\\sqrt{2}\n\\]",
